data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly inject a `ThreadAbortException`. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the catch block will never fire.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces the old ThreadAbortException catch.
                // Clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — cooperative cancellation doesn't
                // auto-rethrow. The finally block runs normally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — replaces Thread.Abort()

        // Give the thread time to finish cleanly
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning — you cannot force-kill a managed thread in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) — a bool can't interrupt a blocked call |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow — no reset needed |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread to finish, not just an arbitrary delay |

## Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Cooperate

The biggest risk is that `GetNextItem()` **blocks** (e.g., on a queue or socket). Cancelling the token does nothing unless that method checks it. You must modify it:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, can't be interrupted
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER — responds to cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection.Take(CancellationToken)
                                // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep` internally, replace with:

```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately when token is cancelled
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1));
```

## Don't Forget

- **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`** — implement `IDisposable` on `BackgroundProcessor` (shown above) to avoid timer/callback leaks.
- **Pass the token through the full call chain** — if `ProcessItem` calls sub-methods, they all need the token. One method that ignores it stalls the entire cancellation.
- **Cancellation is not immediate** — it only takes effect at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem` if needed.
